Acknowledgement of Roles and Responsibilities of kynectors
The client has been informed about and understands the kynectors roles and responsibilities listed below and has been given the opportunity to discuss them.

kynectors are not a health or stop-loss insurance issuer or a subsidiary of a health or stop-loss insurance issuer, is not an association that includes members of the insurance industry or lobbies for the insurance industry, and does not receive any funding or payments from any health or stop-loss insurance issuer in connection with the enrollment of any individuals in a QHP or a non-QHP. kynector will also inform the client of conflicts of interest they might have.

kynector must comply with Marketplace standards for keeping the client’s personally identifiable information (PII) private and secure, must obtain the client’s consent before accessing the client’s PII, and must permit the client to revoke the client’s consent at any time.
kynector will not charge the client a fee for any help provided.
kynector must also meet any applicable state and local requirements when providing services to the client.

kynector did NOT and will NOT (a) act against the client’s best interests, (b) be paid based on number of applications completed or people they assist, (c) provide the client any gifts or promotional products/services over a value of $15, (d) contact the client on a door-to-door or otherwise unless the client has asked for assistance, and (d) contact the client via “robo-calls” or other type of automatic program.
kynector must maintain expertise in eligibility, enrollment, and program specifications for qualified health plans (QHPs) and insurance affordability programs.

kynector must tell the client about the full range of QHP options and insurance affordability programs for which the client may be eligible, which includes: providing the client with fair, accurate, and impartial information that assists the client with submitting a Marketplace eligibility application; clarifying the distinctions among health coverage options, including QHPs; and helping the client make informed decisions during the health coverage selection process.
kynector won’t discriminate against the client based on the client’s race, color, national origin, disability, age, sex, gender identity, or sexual orientation.
kynector must provide the client with information in a way that that meets the client’s cultural and language needs.
kynector must ensure that tools and help provided are accessible and usable for the client if the client has disabilities.
kynector must help the client to select a QHP, if the client wants that help, but kynector can’t and won’t choose a health insurance plan for the client.

kynector must help the client with grievances, complaints, or questions about the client’s health plan, coverage, or a determination under such a plan or coverage, by providing the client with referrals to any applicable office of health insurance consumer assistance or health insurance ombudsman, or any other appropriate state agency or agencies, if the client wants that help.

All kynectors who help the client have been certified by the Marketplace to help consumers after showing that they meet all required standards. All individuals who help the client must complete and receive a passing score in a CMS-approved training course before providing help to consumers and must take continuing education and be certified or recertified each year before they can continue to help consumers.

Provider Summary Report
Get a summary on all our licensed and certified providers.

All STARS is Kentucky's expanded quality rating improvement system for Licensed Type I, Type II and Certified Family Child Care Homes. Programs are rated on a one-to-five STAR level system. All participants in Kentucky All STARS meet specific indicators of quality. Below are the requirements for each STARS level.
· All STARS Level 1: All child care providers with a regular or preliminary license in good standing are automatically enrolled at a Level 1. Programs with a preliminary license must remain at a Level 1.

· All STARS Level 2: 50 percent of teaching staff have professional learning activities in developmental screening. Complete an environmental self-assessment using a valid and reliable tool appropriate for ages/settings of children served. Program/site administrator /director receives 10 hours of professional learning in curriculum, instructional practices and/or teaching and learning OR has an approved early childhood credential or degree. 50 percent of teaching staff receives 10 hours of professional learning in curriculum, instructional practices and/or teaching and learning OR have an approved early childhood credential or degree.

· All STARS Level 3: All required standards as outlined for Level 2. Participate in an environmental observation on a valid and reliable tool. No minimum required score. In addition to the required standards, providers can select from the Standards of Quality to compile 21-30 points to complete the Level 3 Quality Rating.

· All STARS Level 4:All required standards as outlined for Level. Participate in an environmental observation on a valid and reliable tool. Must have a minimum score of 4.0 in all rated classrooms. In addition to the required standards, providers can select from the Standards of Quality to compile 31-40 points required to complete the Level 4 Quality Rating.
· All STARS Level 5: All required standards as outlined for Level 2. Participate in an environmental observation on a valid an reliable tool. Must have a minimum score of 5.0 in all rated classrooms. In addition to the required standards, providers can select from the Standards of Quality to compile 41-50 points required to complete the Level 5 Quality Rating.
For more information, visit the Kentucky All STARS website here: https://chfs.ky.gov/agencies/dcbs/dcc/Pages/kyallstars.aspx
